⚖️ LCES: Legal Calculus Educational System

🟦 The Multi-Agent Architectural Workflow

LCES uses structured role separation to reduce cognitive load and prevent circular reasoning.

Instead of asking one agent to plan, draft, and validate at the same time, LCES separates the workflow into three roles:

🧩 Architect

✍️ Builder

🛡️ Inspector

🔹 Architect — Structural Logic

Focus:

- Issue framing

• Procedural sequence

• Workflow design

• Missing-information mapping

Boundary:

✅ Builds the blueprint

❌ Does not draft full prose

❌ Does not red-team

🔹 Builder — Transformation

Focus:

- Draft filings

• Notices

• Declarations

• Factual summaries

• Proposed orders

Boundary:

✅ Converts structure into prose

❌ Does not redesign the structure

❌ Does not add unsupported strategy

🔹 Inspector — Adversarial Testing

Focus:

- Weakness detection

• Gap identification

• Contradiction flags

• Preservation analysis

Boundary:

✅ Tests whether the work survives scrutiny

❌ Does not rewrite the document

❌ Does not provide legal advice

🟨 Why role separation matters

This model helps LCES:

- Reduce drift

• Prevent premature drafting

• Isolate defects

• Preserve accountability

• Improve structural validation

• Strengthen record discipline

The result is a workflow where each phase is independently tested before the work product moves forward.

⚖️ Plan with structure.

Build with discipline.

Inspect under pressure.

That is the LCES multi-agent workflow.

